[[File:Thalassarche bulleri in flight 1 - SE Tasmania.jpg|thumb|Buller's albatross with a [[short-tailed shearwater]] behind, East of the [[Tasman Peninsula]], [[Tasmania]], Australia]]
'''Buller's albatross''' ('''''Thalassarche bulleri''''') or '''Buller's mollymawk''' is a small [[mollymawk]] in the [[albatross]] [[family (biology)|family]].

It breeds on islands around [[New Zealand]], and feeds in the seas off [[Australia]] and the South [[Pacific]].

==Taxonomy==
Mollymawks are a type of albatross that belong to the family [[Diomedeidae]] of the order [[Procellariiformes]], along with [[shearwater]]s, [[fulmar]]s, [[storm petrel]]s, and [[diving petrel]]s. They share certain identifying features. First, they have nasal passages called [[naricorns]] that attach to the upper bill, although the nostrils on the albatross are on the sides of the bill. The bills of Procellariiformes are also unique in that they are split into seven to nine horny plates. Finally, they produce a [[stomach oil]] made up of [[wax ester]]s and [[triglycerides]] that is stored in the [[proventriculus]]. This is used against predators as well as an energy rich food source for chicks and for the adults during their long flights.<ref>Double, M. C. (2003)</ref> They also have a [[salt gland]] that is situated above the nasal passage and helps desalinate their bodies, due to the large amount of ocean water that they imbibe. It excretes a highly saline solution from their nose.<ref>Ehrlich, Paul R. (1988)</ref>

In 1998, C.J.R. Robertson and G. B. Nunn split this species into two, ''Thalassarche (bulleri) bulleri'', and ''Thalassarche (bulleri) platei'',<ref>Robertson CJR, Nunn GB (1998). "Towards a new taxonomy for albatrosses" in G. Robertson and R. Gales, eds.  '''Albatross Biology and Conservation''. pp13-19.</ref> although the majority of authorities including [[ITIS]],<ref name="ITIS">ITIS</ref> [[James Clements (ornithologist)|James Clements]],<ref name="Clements">Clements, J. (2007)</ref> [[BirdLife International]],<ref name="BLI">BirdLife International (2008)</ref> and Michael Brooke<ref name="Brooke">Brooke, M. (2004)</ref> have not yet accepted this split

==Etymology==
It was named for the New Zealand [[ornithologist]] [[Walter Buller]].

==Description==
Buller's albatross averages {{convert|79|cm|in|abbr=on}}. It has a silver-grey forehead, a grey head and throat. It has a black patch around the eyes with a white crescent behind and below the eye.  Its back, upperwing, and tail are dark grey, and its rump and underparts are white. Its underwing is white with a black tip, with a broad sharply demarcated dark band at the leading edge. Its bill is large and black with yellow on the upper [[mandible]], and the tip. The juvenile has a darker head and a brown bill.<ref name="BLI" />

==Behaviour==

===Reproduction===
The Buller's albatross is [[seabird colony|colonial]], nesting generally on cliffs, steep coastal terraces, grassy meadows, and tussock covered hills.<ref name ="Marchant">Marchant, S. & Higgins, P. J. (1990)</ref> Birds in the [[Snares Islands]] also nest under trees inland.<ref name="BLI" /> The nest is mound of soil, grass and roots and is set into depressions in the breeding area. Breeding begins in December. Eggs on the Snares are laid in late January (around the 21–23 of January).  [[Avian incubation|incubation]] lasts around 60 days, with both parents sharing the responsibility. The average incubation shift is around 10 days. After hatching it takes 170 days to [[fledge]] the chick. They breed annually.<ref name="BLI" />

===Feeding===
Buller's albatross feeds on [[squid]], fish, [[tunicates]], [[octopus]], and [[crustacea]].<ref name="BLI" /><ref name ="James">James, J. D. & Stahl, J. C. (2000)</ref><ref name="west">West, J. A. & Imber, M. G. (1986)</ref>

