Buller's albatross is [[endemism in birds|endemic]] to [[New Zealand]]. They breed on [[Snares Islands]], [[Solander Island]], [[Chatham Islands]] ([[The Sisters/Rangitatahi|Big and Little Sister]] and [[Forty-Fours/Motuhara|Forty-fours Island]]), and [[Three Kings Islands]] ([[Rosemary Rock]]). Adults forage between 40°S and 50°S from [[Tasmania]] to the [[Chatham Rise]].<ref name="StahlA">Stahl, J. C. & Sagar, P. M. (2000)(a)</ref><ref name="StahlB" /><ref name="StahlC">Stahl, J. C., et al. (1998)</ref><ref>BirdLife International (2004)</ref><ref name = "Sagar">Sagar, P. M. & Stahl, J. C. (2005)</ref>  Juveniles and adults that aren't breeding disperse across the South Pacific with a number feeding every year in the [[Humboldt Current]] off [[Chile]] and [[Peru]].<ref name="BLI" /><ref name="StahlB">Stahl, J. C. & Sagar, P. M. (2000)(b)</ref><ref name="Spear">Spear, L. B., et al. (2003)</ref><ref name="Taylor">Taylor, G. A. (2000)</ref>

==Conservation==
[[File:Thalassarche bulleri.jpg|thumb|left|Buller's albatross (''Thalassarche bulleri''). Note the two parasites just under the feathers.]]
It was formerly classified as a [[vulnerable species]] by the [[IUCN]].<ref>Lee, James (6 Oct 2008)</ref> But new research has shown it to be not as rare as it was believed. Consequently, it was downlisted to [[near threatened]] status in 2008.<ref name="iucn status 11 November 2021" /> It has an occurrence range of {{convert|16100000|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}} and a breeding range of {{convert|4|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}. According to a 1999 estimate, there are 64,000 birds and there are 31,939 breeding adults. These are located as follows: 8,877 pairs on the [[Snares Islands]], 4,912 pairs on [[Solander Island]],<ref name="Sagar" /><ref name="SagarB">Sagar, P. M., et al. (1999)</ref> 16,000 pairs on [[Forty-Fours|Forty-fours Island]], 2,130 pairs on [[The Sisters (New Zealand)|Big and Little Sister]], 20 pairs on Rosemary Rock in the Three Kings group.<ref name="Croxall">Croxall, J. P. & Gales, R. (1998)</ref>

The Snares Islands population has been increasing, but lately not as much as in the 1970s,<ref name="Sagar" /><ref name="SagarB" /> whereas the Solander Island population which was stable from 1985 to 1996 has now shown about an 18% increase.<ref name="Sagar" /> The survival rate of adults on the Snares Islands increased to 95.5%<ref name="Sagar2000">Sagar, P. M., et al. (2000)</ref> and brooding success rate was 70.8%,<ref name="Sagar2002">Sagar, P. M., et al. (2002)</ref> whereas on Big and Little Sister, adult survival rate is 93.5% and the brooding success rate is between 57–60%.<ref name="Croxall" />

Buller's albatross is the most common [[bycatch]] from [[longline fishing|longline fisheries]] out of [[New Zealand]],<ref name="Bartle">Bartle, J. A. (1990)</ref><ref name="Murray">Murray, T. E., et al. (1993)</ref> and, even though net-sonde cables were banned in 1992, squid trawlers still catch them.<ref name="Taylor" /> Finally, [[weka]] ''Gallirallus australis'' was introduced to Big Sister and may take eggs and chicks.<ref name="Taylor" /> Most islands are legally protected, except for the [[Chatham Islands]] colonies which are on private land.

